'''Bubbe meise''' or "bobe mayse" {{lang-yi|באבע מאיסע}} is a Yiddish expression meaning "old wives tale", "grandmother's tale", essentially "a fairytale of something impossible". The Yiddish word "bubbe" is close to [[Slavic]] {{lang-ru|баба}} (baba), "grandmother". 

The roots of this expression lie in [[Medieval]] [[Anglo-Norman]] [[chivalry|chivalric]] adventures [[Romance (genre)|romance]] ''[[Bevis of Hampton]]''. Rewritten for [[Jew]]ish audience in [[1507]]–[[1508]]  in Yiddish by [[Elia Levita]], it came to be known as ''Bove meise'' or ''[[Bovo-Bukh]]'' and was the most popular chivalric romance in the Yiddish language for five centuries. 

